<div id="review_3510244090" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3510244090" />
    <a title="Kiran Bhat" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/81560301-kiran-bhat"><img alt="Kiran Bhat" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1525335374p2/81560301.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3510244090?book_show_action=true">Aug 22, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kiran Bhat" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kiran Bhat" href="/user/show/81560301-kiran-bhat">Kiran Bhat</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3510244090" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4776348104029964877">Gorky elicits strange reactions in me. I can totally understand why a certain part of the literary elite don&apos;t like him - too &apos;on-the-nose&apos; with his political ideas, easily veers into melodrama and overt symbolism instead of telling his story from inside of his characters, etc. At the same time, I think there is a certain life in Gorky&apos;s work. It just comes from the veneer of his writing and not the interior. I did feel a lot of pathos for the mother of the narrative, and I felt the pages of the</span>
  <span id="freeText4776348104029964877" style="display:none">Gorky elicits strange reactions in me. I can totally understand why a certain part of the literary elite don't like him - too 'on-the-nose' with his political ideas, easily veers into melodrama and overt symbolism instead of telling his story from inside of his characters, etc. At the same time, I think there is a certain life in Gorky's work. It just comes from the veneer of his writing and not the interior. I did feel a lot of pathos for the mother of the narrative, and I felt the pages of the novel turning quite quickly. I was compelled, and isn't that the best feeling after reading a book, to feel like doing something? So, I get that it's flawed, but I really think it's worth reading, particularly for those who are down-trodden, or are in the mood to change things. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4776348104029964877" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


