  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3409207127" />
    <a title="Luís" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/117399210-lu-s"><img alt="Luís" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1620236159p2/117399210.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3409207127?book_show_action=true">Jun 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Luís" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Luís" href="/user/show/117399210-lu-s">Luís</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9788440709516" href="/book/show/6693054-a-m-e">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=russia-ussr">russia-ussr</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3409207127" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3481925381475854635">Some time ago, this book was in my library. I was delighted to read it, expecting to be in the same lineage as the Tolstoys and other Dostoevsky. However, I did not inquire more than that about its author. Before embarking on hasty and risky comparisons, let&apos;s say a few words of history. <br/>In a working-class village in Russia in the early twentieth century, life is hard and regulated by the factory, it &quot;engulfed the day, the machines sucked into the muscles of men all the forces it needed. The day</span>
  <span id="freeText3481925381475854635" style="display:none">Some time ago, this book was in my library. I was delighted to read it, expecting to be in the same lineage as the Tolstoys and other Dostoevsky. However, I did not inquire more than that about its author. Before embarking on hasty and risky comparisons, let's say a few words of history. <br />In a working-class village in Russia in the early twentieth century, life is hard and regulated by the factory, it "engulfed the day, the machines sucked into the muscles of men all the forces it needed. The day scratched with life without leaving a trace; without noticing it, the man had gone a step further towards his grave; but he could indulge in the enjoyment of repose, in the pleasures of sordid cabaret, and he was satisfied." It is in this deleterious atmosphere that a group of young people will gradually form trying to spread the good socialist news to the factory, in the region, then to the whole of Russia. The book follows the evolution of Pelagia Nilovna Vlassova affectionately nicknamed "The Mother". His son Pavel Vlasov is one of the charismatic leaders of the revolutionary movement. Locked up in a mediocre life, paralyzed by fear and despair, Pélagia will gradually open up to the new ideas of her son and her companions, then participate in the underground actions, and finally, give herself entirely to the socialist cause. <br />The quality of the novel from the strict literary point of view disappointed me. There is certainly a plot, but more than half of the pages are devoted to the moods of the mother very redundant. Hope, despair, sadness, joy, frustration and hope again, all bathed in a sea of tears. As for the situations, they are also often identical, and some statements of the protagonists propose a propaganda a little heavy. Gorky can not get rid of a certain Manichaeism by opposing the good guys to the good ones, whereas a more nuanced approach would have been more realistic. <br />However, the many characters, actors of political, philosophical and social renewal are well dug. Although they are idealized, even caricatural, they say something about the social diversity of the majority of the oppressed. The very first chapter upset me when the author draws the sad scenery in which part of the plot will hold. We feel that a great writer committed, observant, demanding and lucid is at work. As the character of the mother, it is difficult not be moved (despite everything!) by his unshakeable confidence in his son, love and attention to each and his dedication that culminates in his final arrest (another passage of high fly). The caterpillar became a butterfly. <br />If you look at the novel from a social and political point of view, it's more interesting. Indeed, it paints a chilling portrait of the extremely precarious situation of Russia at the very beginning of the 20th century, of the selfish exploitation of man by man, of his miserable and sombre daily life, of the absence of some transcendence. A context that seems to be a breeding ground and justification for the revolutionary ambitions of the workers and peasants; It offers, moreover, an appealing light on the Soviet revolution; if we stick to the causes of the uprising, it seems to start from a good intention. The enthusiasm and serenity of the socialists of the book are quite communicative. The revolution appears necessary to get out of a disgusting system. That said, no one is unaware of the consequences it had on the people it claimed to serve. <br />Without being a connoisseur of Gorky, it seems that the "Soviet realistic" label defines it quite well. I would not allow myself to pass judgment on his political commitments to Lenin. Then to Stalin, it seems that Henri Troyat was able to pin it down in his book Gorky (a future reading?). However, his optimism (and sometimes his naivety) for the "great cause" that transpires through the pages is very touching. I also praise the author for his Faith in man and his rejection of all determinism, no soul is permanently lost. <br />Finally, the novel is captivating because it tells us something of historical socialism that seems very far from the pale and sad reflection offered by our current policies. Anyone interested in the history of ideas and the Russian people should read this book. It is even possible that he sometimes lets himself contaminated by the frenetic enthusiasm and quiet confidence of the characters, some of their speeches are unfortunately more relevant than ever: "We believe that the society which considers man only as a means of enrichment is antihuman, that it is hostile to us; we can not accept her double-faced morality, her shameless cynicism, and the cruelty with which she treats the individualities that are opposed to her; we want to fight, and we will fight against all the forms of physical and moral servitude of the man employed by this society which divides man in favour of greed" or a little further on, "all that you do is criminal, for you think only of enslaving the man; our work to free us from the world of monsters and ghosts created by your lie, your greed, your hatred. Soon the mass of our workers and peasants will be free and will create an open, harmonious and immense world. And that will be!".</span>
  <a data-text-id="3481925381475854635" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


