<div id="review_3314553194" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3314553194" />
    <a title="Fábio Shecaira" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/107860429-f-bio-shecaira"><img alt="Fábio Shecaira" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1584318218p2/107860429.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3314553194?book_show_action=true">May 16, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Fábio Shecaira" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Fábio Shecaira" href="/user/show/107860429-f-bio-shecaira">Fábio Shecaira</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3314553194" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13852245980677261818">I am very interested in socialism and its literary history, but I did not like this book very much. I expected a gripping account of human misery and exploitation, or perhaps an eloquent defense of organized political action by the working class. The book is indeed about class struggle in tsarist Russia, but the story is not very well told. The characters, most of whom are supposed to represent workers, appear in the dialogue as if they were constantly speaking from the soapbox. Their flamboyant</span>
  <span id="freeText13852245980677261818" style="display:none">I am very interested in socialism and its literary history, but I did not like this book very much. I expected a gripping account of human misery and exploitation, or perhaps an eloquent defense of organized political action by the working class. The book is indeed about class struggle in tsarist Russia, but the story is not very well told. The characters, most of whom are supposed to represent workers, appear in the dialogue as if they were constantly speaking from the soapbox. Their flamboyant rhetoric is unrealistic, repetitive, and tedious.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13852245980677261818" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


