<div id="review_394407502" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/394407502" />
    <a title="Neil Crossan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4253412-neil-crossan"><img alt="Neil Crossan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1359523061p2/4253412.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/394407502?book_show_action=true">Aug 17, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Neil Crossan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Neil Crossan" href="/user/show/4253412-neil-crossan">Neil Crossan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Workers</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Neil by: </span>
      The Nation
  </div>


    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer394407502" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12848607638658750676">It really is amazing just how shitty life was for most workers 100 years ago. Thank God we have moved forward as a society … what’s that? 34 striking miners in South Africa were killed by police and most were shot in the back? Awesome. Better let the NFL Referees know so they can end their strike. What’s that? They weren’t striking? They weren’t even intending to strike? They were just locked out by the owners because the owners thought they could get others to do it cheaper?<br/><br/>As American workers </span>
  <span id="freeText12848607638658750676" style="display:none">It really is amazing just how shitty life was for most workers 100 years ago. Thank God we have moved forward as a society … what’s that? 34 striking miners in South Africa were killed by police and most were shot in the back? Awesome. Better let the NFL Referees know so they can end their strike. What’s that? They weren’t striking? They weren’t even intending to strike? They were just locked out by the owners because the owners thought they could get others to do it cheaper?<br /><br />As American workers across the salary spectrum continue to lose benefits like collective bargaining, pensions, 401K matching, health benefits or their jobs to cheaper labor pools it is easy to appreciate the message of workers bonding together for a collective good that Gorky delivers. Now, I doubt the American worker would be receptive to Gorky due to the Soviet packaging, but in a time of dwindling worker power it’s an interesting read about exploited workers in 1906. It is not a complex story as most of the other characters play singular roles in support of the Mother’s transition from domestic abuse victim to police brutality victim. And at times the chapters can repeat the same themes, but there are also passages of community that get to the optimistic heart of Gorky’s message. If you read this for the story itself, I think you’ll be bored. If you read it for it’s historical context, you’ll still be bored but much less of the time. And you’ll get some insights to some of the motivations for the Russian Revolutions.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12848607638658750676" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


